value.value: A region of sequence implicated in an experimental result.

A region (or regions) that includes all of the sequence elements necessary to encode a functional transcript. A gene may include regulatory regions, transcribed regions and/or other functional sequence regions.

definition.value: This term is mapped to MGED. Do not obsolete without consulting MGED ontology. A gene may be considered as a unit of inheritance.

value.value: Two or more adjacent copies of a region (of length greater than 1).
The 3' splice site of the acceptor primary transcript.

definition.value: This region contains a polypyridine tract and AG dinucleotide in some organisms and is UUUCAG in C. elegans.

value.value: The 5' five prime splice site region of the donor RNA.

definition.value: SL RNA contains a donor site.

value.value: A trans_splicing_acceptor_site which appends the 22nt SL1 RNA leader sequence to the 5' end of most mRNAs.
A trans_splicing_acceptor_site which appends the 22nt SL2 RNA leader sequence to the 5' end of mRNAs. SL2 acceptor sites occur in genes in internal segments of polycistronic transcripts.
A gene encoding an mRNA that has the stop codon redefined as selenocysteine.
A gene with mRNA recoded by translational bypass.
A gene encoding a transcript that has a translational frameshift.
A motif that is active in the DNA form of the sequence.
A region of nucleotide sequence corresponding to a known motif.
A motif that is active in RNA sequence.
An mRNA that has the quality dicistronic.
A nucleic acid sequence that when read as sequential triplets, has the potential of encoding a sequential string of amino acids. It need not contain the start or stop codon.

definition.value: This term was added after a request by SGD. August 2004. Modified after SO meeting in Cambridge to not include start or stop.

value.value: A reading_frame that is interrupted by one or more stop codons; usually identified through inter-genomic sequence comparisons.

definition.value: Term requested by Rama from SGD.

value.value: An ordered and oriented set of scaffolds based on somewhat weaker sets of inferential evidence such as one set of mate pair reads together with supporting evidence from ESTs or location of markers from SNP or microsatellite maps, or cytogenetic localization of contained markers.
A transposable element that is foreign.

definition.value: requested by Michael on 19 Nov 2004.

value.value: A gene that encodes a dicistronic primary transcript.

definition.value: Requested by Michael, 19 nov 2004.

value.value: A gene that encodes a polycistronic mRNA.

definition.value: Requested by MA nov 19 2004.

value.value: Genomic sequence removed from the genome, as a normal event, by a process of recombination.
A region of a DNA molecule where transfer is initiated during the process of conjugation or mobilization.
The transit_peptide is a short region at the N-terminus of the peptide that directs the protein to an organelle (chloroplast, mitochondrion, microbody or cyanelle).

definition.value: Added to bring SO inline with the EMBL, DDBJ, GenBank feature table. Old definition before biosapiens: The coding sequence for an N-terminal domain of a nuclear-encoded organellar protein. This domain is involved in post translational import of the protein into the organelle.

value.value: The simplest repeated component of a repeat region. A single repeat.

definition.value: Added to comply with the feature table. A single repeat.

value.value: A regulatory region where transcription factor binding sites are clustered to regulate various aspects of transcription activities. (CRMs can be located a few kb to hundreds of kb upstream of the core promoter, in the coding sequence, within introns, or in the untranslated regions (UTR) sequences, and even on a different chromosome). A single gene can be regulated by multiple CRMs to give precise control of its spatial and temporal expression. CRMs function as nodes in large, intertwined regulatory network. CRM DNA accessibility is subject to regulation by dbTFs and transcription co-TFs.

definition.value: Requested by Stephen Grossmann Dec 2004. Changed relationship from has_part SO:0000235 TF_binding site to TF_binding_site is part_of SO:0000727 CRM in response to requests from GREEKC initiative in Aug 2020. Removed 3' from definition because 5' UTRs are included as well, notified by Colin Logie of GREEKC. Nov 9 2020. DS Updated name from 'CRM' to 'cis_regulatory_module' on 08 Feb 2021. See GitHub Issue #526. DS Added final sentence to definition as part of GREEKC Feb 16, 2021. See GitHub Issue #534.

value.value: A region of a peptide that is able to excise itself and rejoin the remaining portions with a peptide bond.

definition.value: Intein-mediated protein splicing occurs after mRNA has been translated into a protein.

value.value: An attribute of protein-coding genes where the initial protein product contains an intein.
A gap in the sequence of known length. The unknown bases are filled in with N's.
An attribute to describe a feature that is incomplete.

definition.value: Term added because of request by MO people.

value.value: An attribute describing an unverified region.
An attribute describing a located_sequence_feature.

An exemplar is a representative cDNA sequence for each gene. The exemplar approach is a method that usually involves some initial clustering into gene groups and the subsequent selection of a representative from each gene group.

definition.value: Added for the MO people.
The location of a sequence.
A sequence of DNA that originates from a an organelle.
DNA belonging to the genome of a mitochondria.
This term is mapped to MGED. Do not obsolete without consulting MGED ontology.
DNA belonging to the nuclear genome of cell.
Moved from is_a SO:0000736 (organelle_sequence) when brought to our attention by GitHub issue #489.
DNA belonging to the genome of a plastid such as a chloroplast. The nucleomorph is the nuclei of the plastic.
DNA belonging to the genome of a plastid such as a chloroplast.

value.value: A kinetoplast is an interlocked network of thousands of minicircles and tens of maxicircles, located near the base of the flagellum of some protozoan species.
A maxicircle is a replicon, part of a kinetoplast, that contains open reading frames and replicates via a rolling circle method.

definition.value: DNA belonging to the genome of an apicoplast, a non-photosynthetic plastid.
DNA belonging to the genome of a chromoplast, a colored plastid for synthesis and storage of pigments.
DNA belonging to the genome of a chloroplast, a green plastid for photosynthesis.
DNA belonging to the genome of a cyanelle, a photosynthetic plastid found in algae.
DNA belonging to the genome of a leucoplast, a colorless plastid generally containing starch or oil.
DNA belonging to the genome of a proplastid such as an immature chloroplast.
The location of DNA that has come from a plasmid sequence.

value.value: An origin_of_replication that is used for the amplification of a chromosomal nucleic acid sequence.

definition.value: The location of DNA that has come from a viral origin.

value.value: The region of sequence that has been inserted and is being propagated by the clone.
